import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
import umap
import hdbscan
from itertools import product
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import warnings
import matplotlib.cm as cm
import matplotlib.colors as mcolors
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=FutureWarning)
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)
# Configure font settings
plt.rcParams["font.family"] = "Times New Roman"
plt.rcParams["font.size"] = 12  # or your preferred size


# Sample data  replace this with your own DataFrame
df = pd.read_csv("reviews_final.csv")  # Example
df_numeric = df.select_dtypes(include='number')
X = df_numeric.drop(columns=['Rating','Word Count']) 


# Step 1: Standardise data
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Step 2: UMAP dimensionality reduction
umap_model = umap.UMAP(n_components=2, random_state=42)
X_umap = umap_model.fit_transform(X_scaled)

# Step 3: Grid search over HDBSCAN parameters
min_cluster_sizes = [5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40]
min_samples_list = [5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35]

results = []

for min_cluster_size, min_samples in product(min_cluster_sizes, min_samples_list):
    clusterer = hdbscan.HDBSCAN(min_cluster_size=min_cluster_size,
                                min_samples=min_samples,
                                prediction_data=True)
    labels = clusterer.fit_predict(X_umap)
    
    mask = labels != -1
    if len(set(labels[mask])) > 1:
        sil_score = silhouette_score(X_umap[mask], labels[mask])
    else:
        sil_score = -1  # Invalid silhouette (only one cluster or none)

    n_clusters = len(set(labels)) - (1 if -1 in labels else 0)
    noise_fraction = np.sum(labels == -1) / len(labels)

    results.append({
        'min_cluster_size': min_cluster_size,
        'min_samples': min_samples,
        'n_clusters': n_clusters,
        'silhouette_score': sil_score,
        'noise_fraction': noise_fraction
    })

# Convert results to DataFrame
results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)
results_df = results_df.sort_values(by='silhouette_score', ascending=False)

# Print top results
print(results_df.head())

# Optional: visualise best result
best = results_df.iloc[0]
best_clusterer = hdbscan.HDBSCAN(min_cluster_size=int(best['min_cluster_size']),
                                 min_samples=int(best['min_samples']),
                                 prediction_data=True)
best_labels = best_clusterer.fit_predict(X_umap)

from scipy.stats import kruskal
from statsmodels.stats.multitest import multipletests

# Keep only non-noise points
mask = new_labels != 0
X_original_masked = X.loc[mask]
labels_masked = best_labels[mask]

# Run KruskalWallis test for each feature
kruskal_results = {}

for col in X_original_masked.columns:
    groups = [X_original_masked[col][labels_masked == label] for label in np.unique(labels_masked)]
    stat, p = kruskal(*groups)
    kruskal_results[col] = {'statistic': stat, 'p_value': p}

# Convert to DataFrame
kruskal_df = pd.DataFrame(kruskal_results).T

# Apply FDR correction
pvals = kruskal_df['p_value'].values
_, pvals_fdr, _, _ = multipletests(pvals, method='fdr_bh')

# Add adjusted p-values to DataFrame
kruskal_df['p_fdr'] = pvals_fdr

# Sort by corrected p-value
kruskal_df = kruskal_df.sort_values(by='p_fdr')

print(kruskal_df)

from sklearn.metrics import adjusted_rand_score

def compute_ari_reference(X_umap, original_labels, min_cluster_size, min_samples, n_runs=10):
    ari_scores = []
    
    for seed in range(10, 10 + n_runs):
        # Add a tiny bit of noise
        X_noisy = X_umap + np.random.normal(0, 0.01, X_umap.shape)
        
        # Refit HDBSCAN
        clusterer = hdbscan.HDBSCAN(min_cluster_size=min_cluster_size,
                                    min_samples=min_samples,
                                    prediction_data=True)
        test_labels = clusterer.fit_predict(X_noisy)
        
        # ARI compares *all* labelings; noise must be handled
        mask = (original_labels != -1) & (test_labels != -1)
        if np.sum(mask) > 0:
            ari = adjusted_rand_score(original_labels[mask], test_labels[mask])
            ari_scores.append(ari)

    return ari_scores

ari_scores = compute_ari_reference(
    X_umap=X_umap,
    original_labels=best_labels,
    min_cluster_size=int(best['min_cluster_size']),
    min_samples=int(best['min_samples']),
    n_runs=10
)

print("ARI Scores (robustness across resampling):")
print(ari_scores)
print(f"Mean ARI: {np.mean(ari_scores):.4f}  {np.std(ari_scores):.4f}")

from sklearn.metrics import pairwise_distances
import numpy as np
from itertools import combinations

def jaccard_index(labels1, labels2):
    """
    Compute Jaccard Index between two cluster labelings.
    labels1 and labels2 should be 1D numpy arrays with same length.
    """
    n = len(labels1)
    assert n == len(labels2), "Cluster label vectors must be the same length"
    
    # Initialize counters
    m11 = m10 = m01 = 0

    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(i+1, n):
            same_cluster1 = labels1[i] == labels1[j]
            same_cluster2 = labels2[i] == labels2[j]

            if same_cluster1 and same_cluster2:
                m11 += 1
            elif same_cluster1 and not same_cluster2:
                m10 += 1
            elif not same_cluster1 and same_cluster2:
                m01 += 1
            # else: both in different clusters  not counted in numerator or denominator

    denominator = m11 + m10 + m01
    if denominator == 0:
        return 1.0  # all points in different clusters in both labelings
    return m11 / denominator


# Run HDBSCAN twice with same UMAP but different parameters or subsample
clusterer1 = hdbscan.HDBSCAN(min_cluster_size=20, min_samples=10)

clusterer2 = hdbscan.HDBSCAN(min_cluster_size=25, min_samples=15)
labels2 = clusterer2.fit_predict(X_umap)

# Filter out noise (optional)
mask = (labels1 != -1) & (labels2 != -1)
jaccard = jaccard_index(labels1[mask], labels2[mask])
print(f"Jaccard Index between two clusterings (excluding noise): {jaccard:.4f}")

#df.to_csv("reviews_final_clusters.csv", index=False)

From an exploratory research standpoint, the choice of cluster granularity should be guided by the analytical objective rather than purely by statistical stability metrics. In this context, the aim is to interrogate the structure of customer reviews in terms of sentiment polarity, discrete emotional expressions, and topic-specific concerns, rather than to optimise for maximum clustering robustness or predictive accuracy.

While the two-cluster configuration derived from the UMAPHDBSCAN pipeline demonstrates superior stability indices, including a higher silhouette score and greater reproducibility across resampling, its interpretive resolution is inherently limited. This bifurcated solution essentially collapses the review corpus into a dichotomy of predominantly positive versus predominantly negative experiential profiles, which constrains the capacity to uncover more subtle heterogeneity in customer narratives.

Conversely, the four-cluster configuration, despite exhibiting lower mean Adjusted Rand Index and moderate separation quality, affords a richer qualitative segmentation. Specifically, it differentiates between multiple subtypes within both positive and negative valence domainssuch as highly engaged, verbose positive reviewers versus concise, affirmatory respondents on the positive side, and complaint-driven, issue-saturated reviews versus ambivalent or mixed-experience reviews on the negative side. This additional granularity facilitates a more nuanced interrogation of co-occurring sentimentemotiontopic patterns, enabling the identification of distinct customer archetypes and the mapping of specific product or service attributes to discrete experiential subgroups.

Therefore, for the stated objective of exploring reviews and customer experience from an integrated sentiment, emotion, and topic perspective, the four-cluster solution is preferable. Its capacity to reveal fine-grained variations in emotional tone and thematic content outweighs the drawbacks associated with reduced statistical robustness, as the principal aim is interpretive richness rather than generalisability.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.stats import pearsonr

# Function to compute p-values matrix
def calculate_pvalues(df):
    pvalues = pd.DataFrame(np.ones((df.shape[1], df.shape[1])), columns=df.columns, index=df.columns)
    for i in range(df.shape[1]):
        for j in range(i + 1, df.shape[1]):
            _, p = pearsonr(df.iloc[:, i], df.iloc[:, j])
            pvalues.iloc[i, j] = p
            pvalues.iloc[j, i] = p
    return pvalues

# Function to format correlation coefficients with significance stars
def format_corr_with_asterisks(corr, pvals):
    annot = corr.copy().astype(str)
    for i in range(corr.shape[0]):
        for j in range(corr.shape[1]):
            r = corr.iloc[i, j]
            p = pvals.iloc[i, j]
            if p < 0.001:
                annot.iloc[i, j] = f"{r:.2f}***"
            elif p < 0.01:
                annot.iloc[i, j] = f"{r:.2f}**"
            elif p < 0.05:
                annot.iloc[i, j] = f"{r:.2f}*"
            else:
                annot.iloc[i, j] = f"{r:.2f}"
    return annot

# Function to plot correlation heatmap for one cluster
def plot_cluster_correlation(cluster_df, cluster_label):
    cluster_numeric = cluster_df.select_dtypes(include='number').drop(columns=['Cluster', 'Word Count'], errors='ignore')
    
    if cluster_numeric.shape[1] < 2:
        print(f"Cluster {cluster_label} skipped (less than 2 numeric columns).")
        return
    
    corr = cluster_numeric.corr()
    pvals = calculate_pvalues(cluster_numeric)
    annot = format_corr_with_asterisks(corr, pvals)
    
    mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr, dtype=bool))
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 12))
    sns.heatmap(
        corr,
        mask=mask,
        cmap='coolwarm',
        center=0,
        annot=annot,
        fmt="",
        linewidths=0.4,
        square=True,
        cbar=False,   # <---- turn off the colorbar
        #cbar_kws={"shrink": 0.85, "label": "Correlation"},
        annot_kws={"size": 8, "color": "black"}
    )
    
    plt.title(f"Feature Correlation Heatmap  Cluster {cluster_label}", fontsize=16)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=12)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=12)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Main function to plot heatmaps for each cluster
def plot_correlation_by_cluster(df, cluster_col='Cluster'):
    plt.rcParams["font.family"] = "Times New Roman"
    clusters = sorted(df[cluster_col].unique())  # Sorts numerically from -1 upwards
    
    for cluster in clusters:
        cluster_df = df[df[cluster_col] == cluster]
        plot_cluster_correlation(cluster_df, cluster)

# Example usage:
plot_correlation_by_cluster(df, cluster_col='Cluster')
